data.content:
## Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` in `ProcessLoop` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block rolling back transaction | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** | Prevents rethrow so `finally` runs cleanly | No longer needed — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |

The core problem: `GetNextItem()` **blocks**, so setting `_running = false` alone won't wake it. The original code falls back to `Thread.Abort()` to force-terminate the blocked call. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply doesn't work.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work, then exit
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for clean shutdown
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(2000));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical: You Must Fix `GetNextItem`

The migration **only works** if `GetNextItem` actually observes the token. This is the #1 pitfall — if the blocking call ignores the token, cancellation stalls there indefinitely.

**If it reads from a `BlockingCollection<T>`** (common pattern):
```csharp
// Before — blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could break it
var item = _queue.Take();

// After — throws OperationCanceledException when token is cancelled
var item = _queue.Take(token);
```

**If it does synchronous I/O** (socket, database, etc.):
```csharp
// Before — blocks on a synchronous read
var data = stream.Read(buffer, 0, buffer.Length);

// After — use async I/O with the token
var bytesRead = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token);
```

**If it wraps `WaitHandle` / `ManualResetEvent`**:
```csharp
// Before
_signal.WaitOne();

// After — wakes up on either the signal OR cancellation
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | If `GetNextItem` or `ProcessItem` don't accept the token, cancellation can't interrupt them. Every blocking/long-running method must forward it. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` removal** | `OperationCanceledException` does NOT auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did — simply delete the `ResetAbort` call. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()`** | Replaced with `Thread.Join(timeout)` — this actually waits for the thread to finish rather than blindly sleeping and hoping. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class ensures cleanup. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from inner code. |
| **Assuming cancellation is immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort` (which injected an exception anywhere), cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations in `ProcessItem` too. |

## What Changed Conceptually

```
.NET Framework (preemptive)          .NET 8 (cooperative)
─────────────────────────────        ─────────────────────────────
Runtime injects exception            Code must voluntarily check
at arbitrary point                   at explicit checkpoints

Thread.Abort()                  →    CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()
catch (ThreadAbortException)    →    catch (OperationCanceledException)
Thread.ResetAbort()             →    (delete — not needed)
volatile bool _running          →    CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested
Thread.Sleep() in Stop          →    Thread.Join(timeout)
```

The fundamental shift: **nothing can force-stop your code anymore**. Every blocking call must accept and respect the `CancellationToken`, or it simply won't stop.
